#. type: Title ===
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "Zero Config Setup (Dev Services)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:49
msgid "When testing or running in dev mode Quarkus can even provide you with a zero config database out of the box, a feature we refer to as Dev Services. Depending on your database type you may need Docker installed in order to use this feature.  Dev Services is supported for the following databases:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:51
msgid "DB2 (container) (requires license acceptance)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:52
msgid "Derby (in-process)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:53
msgid "H2 (in-process)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:54
msgid "MariaDB (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:55
msgid "Microsoft SQL Server (container) (requires license acceptance)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:56
msgid "MySQL (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:57
msgid "Oracle Express Edition (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:58
msgid "PostgreSQL (container)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:62
msgid "If you want to use Dev Services then all you need to do is include the relevant extension for the type of database you want (either reactive or JDBC, or both), and don't configure a database URL, username and password, Quarkus will provide the database and you can just start coding without worrying about config."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:68
msgid "If you are using a proprietary database such as DB2 or MSSQL you will need to accept the license agreement. To do this create a `src/main/resources/container-license-acceptance.txt` files in your project and add a line with the image name and tag of the database. By default Quarkus uses the default image for the current version of Testcontainers, if you attempt to start Quarkus the resulting failure will tell you the exact image name in use for you to add to the file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:70
msgid "An example file is shown below:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Block title
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "src/main/resources/container-license-acceptance.txt"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:75
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"ibmcom/db2:11.5.0.0a\n"
"mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2017-CU12\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:80
msgid "All services based on containers are run using Testcontainers but Quarkus is not using the Testcontainers JDBC driver."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:83
msgid "Thus, even though extra JDBC URL properties can be set in your `application.properties` file, specific properties supported by the Testcontainers JDBC driver such as `TC_INITSCRIPT`, `TC_INITFUNCTION`, `TC_DAEMON`, `TC_TMPFS` are not supported."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:86
msgid "Quarkus can support specific properties sent to the container itself though and, typically, this is the case for `TC_MY_CNF` which allows to override the MariaDB/MySQL configuration file."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:88
msgid "Overriding the MariaDB/MySQL configuration would be done as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "quarkus.datasource.devservices.container-properties.TC_MY_CNF=testcontainers/mysql-conf\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:95
msgid "This support is database specific and needs to be implemented in each dev service specifically."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:97
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:188
#, no-wrap
msgid "JDBC datasource"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:100
msgid "Add the `agroal` extension plus one of `jdbc-db2`, `jdbc-derby`, `jdbc-h2`, `jdbc-mariadb`, `jdbc-mssql`, `jdbc-mysql`, `jdbc-oracle` or `jdbc-postgresql`."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:102
msgid "Then configure your datasource:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:108
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:128
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"quarkus.datasource.db-kind=postgresql <1>\n"
"quarkus.datasource.username=<your username>\n"
"quarkus.datasource.password=<your password>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"quarkus.datasource.jdbc.url=jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/hibernate_orm_test\n"
"quarkus.datasource.jdbc.max-size=16\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:115
msgid "If you only have a single JDBC extension, or you are running tests and only have a single test scoped JDBC extension installed then this is optional. If there is only one possible extension we assume this is the correct one, and if a driver has been added with test scope then we assume that this should be used in testing."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:116
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:356
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reactive datasource"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:120
msgid "Add the correct reactive extension for the database you are using: `reactive-db2-client`, `reactive-mssql-client`, `reactive-mysql-client`, `reactive-oracle-client`, or `reactive-pg-client`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:122
msgid "Then configure your reactive datasource:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:131
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:382
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"quarkus.datasource.reactive.url=postgresql:///your_database\n"
"quarkus.datasource.reactive.max-size=20\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:133
msgid "As specified above this is optional."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:134
#, no-wrap
msgid "Default datasource"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:138
msgid "A datasource can be either a JDBC datasource, a reactive one or both.  It all depends on how you configure it and which extensions you added to your project."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:141
msgid "To define a datasource, start with the following (note that this is only required if you have more than one database type installed):"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:145
#, no-wrap
msgid "quarkus.datasource.db-kind=h2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:148
msgid "The database kind defines which type of database you will connect to."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:150
msgid "We currently include these built-in database kinds:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:152
msgid "DB2: `db2`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:153
msgid "Derby: `derby`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:154
msgid "H2: `h2`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:155
msgid "MariaDB: `mariadb`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:156
msgid "Microsoft SQL Server: `mssql`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:157
msgid "MySQL: `mysql`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:158
msgid "Oracle: `oracle`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:159
msgid "PostgreSQL: `postgresql`, `pgsql` or `pg`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:165
msgid "Giving Quarkus the database kind you are targeting will facilitate configuration.  By using a JDBC driver extension and setting the kind in the configuration, Quarkus resolves the JDBC driver automatically, so you don't need to configure it yourself.  If you want to use a database kind that is not part of the built-in ones, use `other` and define the JDBC driver explicitly."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:170
msgid "You can use any JDBC driver in a Quarkus app in JVM mode (see <<other-databases,Using other databases>>).  It is unlikely that it will work when compiling your application to a native executable though."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:172
msgid "If you plan to make a native executable, we recommend you use the existing JDBC Quarkus extensions (or contribute one for your driver)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:175
msgid "There is a good chance you will need to define some credentials to access your database."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:177
msgid "This is done by configuring the following properties:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:182
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"quarkus.datasource.username=<your username>\n"
"quarkus.datasource.password=<your password>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:185
msgid "You can also retrieve the password from Vault by link:{vault-datasource-guide}[using a credential provider] for your datasource."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:187
msgid "Once you have defined the database kind and the credentials, you are ready to configure either a JDBC datasource, a reactive one, or both."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: upstream/_versions/main/guides/datasource.adoc:192
msgid "JDBC is the most common database connection pattern.  You typically need a JDBC datasource when using Hibernate ORM."
msgstr ""

